{
  "verses": [
    {
      "verse_num": "1",
      "segments": [
        {
          "type": "narrative",
          "text": "Don’t boast about tomorrow; for you don’t know what a day may bring."
        }
      ],
      "footnotes": [],
      "references": []
    },
    {
      "verse_num": "2",
      "segments": [
        {
          "type": "narrative",
          "text": "Let another man praise you, and not your own mouth;"
        },
        {
          "type": "narrative",
          "text": "a stranger, and not your own lips."
        }
      ],
      "footnotes": [],
      "references": []
    },
    {
      "verse_num": "3",
      "segments": [
        {
          "type": "narrative",
          "text": "A stone is heavy, and sand is a burden;"
        },
        {
          "type": "narrative",
          "text": "but a fool’s provocation is heavier than both."
        }
      ],
      "footnotes": [],
      "references": []
    },
    {
      "verse_num": "4",
      "segments": [
        {
          "type": "narrative",
          "text": "Wrath is cruel, and anger is overwhelming;"
        },
        {
          "type": "narrative",
          "text": "but who is able to st and before jealousy?"
        }
      ],
      "footnotes": [],
      "references": []
    },
    {
      "verse_num": "5",
      "segments": [
        {
          "type": "narrative",
          "text": "Better is open rebukethan hidden love."
        }
      ],
      "footnotes": [],
      "references": []
    },
    {
      "verse_num": "6",
      "segments": [
        {
          "type": "narrative",
          "text": "The wounds of a friend are faithful, although the kisses of an enemy are profuse."
        }
      ],
      "footnotes": [],
      "references": []
    },
    {
      "verse_num": "7",
      "segments": [
        {
          "type": "narrative",
          "text": "A full soul loathes a honeycomb; but to a hungry soul, every bitter thing is sweet."
        }
      ],
      "footnotes": [],
      "references": []
    },
    {
      "verse_num": "8",
      "segments": [
        {
          "type": "narrative",
          "text": "As a bird that wanders from her nest, so is a man who wanders from his home."
        }
      ],
      "footnotes": [],
      "references": []
    },
    {
      "verse_num": "9",
      "segments": [
        {
          "type": "narrative",
          "text": "Perfume and incense bring joy to the heart; so does earnest counsel from a man’s friend."
        }
      ],
      "footnotes": [],
      "references": []
    },
    {
      "verse_num": "10",
      "segments": [
        {
          "type": "narrative",
          "text": "Don’t forsake your friend and your father’s friend. Don’t go to your brother’s house in the day of your disaster."
        },
        {
          "type": "narrative",
          "text": "A neighbor who is near is better than a distant brother."
        }
      ],
      "footnotes": [],
      "references": []
    },
    {
      "verse_num": "11",
      "segments": [
        {
          "type": "narrative",
          "text": "Be wise, my son, and bring joy to my heart,"
        },
        {
          "type": "narrative",
          "text": "then I can answer my tormentor."
        }
      ],
      "footnotes": [],
      "references": []
    },
    {
      "verse_num": "12",
      "segments": [
        {
          "type": "narrative",
          "text": "A prudent man sees danger and takes refuge; but the simple pass on, and suffer for it."
        }
      ],
      "footnotes": [],
      "references": []
    },
    {
      "verse_num": "13",
      "segments": [
        {
          "type": "narrative",
          "text": "Take his garment when he puts up collateral for a stranger. Hold it for a wayward woman!"
        }
      ],
      "footnotes": [],
      "references": []
    },
    {
      "verse_num": "14",
      "segments": [
        {
          "type": "narrative",
          "text": "He who blesses his neighbor with a loud voice early in the morning, it will be taken as a curse by him."
        }
      ],
      "footnotes": [],
      "references": []
    },
    {
      "verse_num": "15",
      "segments": [
        {
          "type": "narrative",
          "text": "A continual dropping on a rainy day and a contentious wife are alike:"
        }
      ],
      "footnotes": [],
      "references": []
    },
    {
      "verse_num": "16",
      "segments": [
        {
          "type": "narrative",
          "text": "restraining her is like restraining the wind, or like grasping oil in his right hand."
        }
      ],
      "footnotes": [],
      "references": []
    },
    {
      "verse_num": "17",
      "segments": [
        {
          "type": "narrative",
          "text": "Iron sharpens iron; so a man sharpens his friend’s countenance."
        }
      ],
      "footnotes": [],
      "references": []
    },
    {
      "verse_num": "18",
      "segments": [
        {
          "type": "narrative",
          "text": "Whoever tends the fig tree shall eat its fruit. He who looks after his master shall be honored."
        }
      ],
      "footnotes": [],
      "references": []
    },
    {
      "verse_num": "19",
      "segments": [
        {
          "type": "narrative",
          "text": "Like water reflects a face, so a man’s heart reflects the man."
        }
      ],
      "footnotes": [],
      "references": []
    },
    {
      "verse_num": "20",
      "segments": [
        {
          "type": "narrative",
          "text": "Sheol[^12] and Abaddon are never satisfied; and a man’s eyes are never satisfied."
        }
      ],
      "footnotes": [],
      "references": []
    },
    {
      "verse_num": "21",
      "segments": [
        {
          "type": "narrative",
          "text": "The crucible is for silver, and the furnace for gold;"
        },
        {
          "type": "narrative",
          "text": "but man is refined by his praise."
        }
      ],
      "footnotes": [],
      "references": []
    },
    {
      "verse_num": "22",
      "segments": [
        {
          "type": "narrative",
          "text": "Though you grind a fool in a mortar with a pestle along with grain, yet his foolishness will not be removed from him."
        }
      ],
      "footnotes": [],
      "references": []
    },
    {
      "verse_num": "23",
      "segments": [
        {
          "type": "narrative",
          "text": "Know well the state of your flocks, and pay attention to your herds,"
        }
      ],
      "footnotes": [],
      "references": []
    },
    {
      "verse_num": "24",
      "segments": [
        {
          "type": "narrative",
          "text": "for riches are not forever, nor does the crown endure to all generations."
        }
      ],
      "footnotes": [],
      "references": []
    },
    {
      "verse_num": "25",
      "segments": [
        {
          "type": "narrative",
          "text": "The hay is removed, and the new growth appears, the grasses of the hills are gathered in."
        }
      ],
      "footnotes": [],
      "references": []
    },
    {
      "verse_num": "26",
      "segments": [
        {
          "type": "narrative",
          "text": "The lambs are for your clothing, and the goats are the price of a field."
        }
      ],
      "footnotes": [],
      "references": []
    },
    {
      "verse_num": "27",
      "segments": [
        {
          "type": "narrative",
          "text": "There will be plenty of goats’ milk for your food, for your family’s food,"
        },
        {
          "type": "narrative",
          "text": "and for the nourishment of your servant girls."
        }
      ],
      "footnotes": [],
      "references": []
    }
  ]
}